Pirate Adventure (1978) - Modern Reconstruction

A Tribute by Barry Curran, the Architect

ðŸ´â€â˜ ï¸ Overview

This project is a faithful reconstruction of the 1978 classic "Pirate Adventure" (also known as Pirate Cove), originally created by Scott Adams and Alexis Adams.

This version brings the foundational text-based adventure into the modern era using a single-file HTML5/JavaScript engine. It maintains the original Verb-Noun parser logic while introducing dynamic visual synthesis and a retro-terminal aesthetic.

ðŸŽ–ï¸ Credit & Homage

Original Author: Scott Adams (Adventure International)
Release Year: 1978

This reconstruction is dedicated as an homage to the countless hours spent playing this game on the Texas Instruments 99/4A during the early 1980s. This project was born out of a desire to share the magic of early interactive fiction with a new generationâ€”specifically my sonâ€”recreating the same sense of wonder we felt navigating from a London flat to a tropical island in search of treasure.

ðŸ› ï¸ How It Was Reconstructed

The game engine was "up-coded" from the original BASIC logic published in historical archives (such as BYTE Magazine, Dec 1980).

The Parser: Rebuilt in JavaScript to handle the classic two-word input system (Verb-Noun).

The Logic: Every room ID, item flag, and "magic word" (like YOHO) has been mapped to match the original game's difficulty and behavior.

Visuals: Integrated a modern generative image component that creates 8-bit, pixelated scene art based on the room descriptions to enhance immersion.

Interface: Styled with a "CRT Terminal" effect, complete with scanlines and glitch text to evoke the feeling of 1980s computing.

ðŸš€ How to Use

This game is designed for maximum portability and ease of use. It requires no installation.

On a Computer (PC/Mac/Linux):

Download the pirate_adventure.html file.

Right-click the file and select Open With -> 

$$Your Web Browser$$

 (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, or Edge).

Type commands into the terminal and press Enter.

On a Smartphone (iOS/Android):

Upload the pirate_adventure.html file to a cloud service (like iCloud, Google Drive, or Dropbox) or host it via GitHub Pages.

Open the file link in your mobile browser.

The interface is responsive and will adapt to your screen.

